5|$|<b>The</b> <b>Houston</b> riot of 1917 {{disturbed}} Du Bois {{and was a}} major setback {{to efforts}} to permit African Americans to become military officers. The riot began after <b>Houston</b> <b>police</b> arrested and beat two black soldiers; in response, over 100 black soldiers took to <b>the</b> streets of <b>Houston</b> and killed 16 whites. A military court martial was held, and 19 of the soldiers were hung, and 67 others were imprisoned. In spite of <b>the</b> <b>Houston</b> riot, Du Bois and others successfully pressed the Army to accept the officers trained at Spingarn's camp, resulting in over 600 black officers joining the Army in October 1917.|$|R
